'''Amadou Ba Zeund Georges Mvom Onana''' (born 16 August 2001) is a Belgian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for {{English football updater|AstonVil}} club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. Born in Senegal, he represents the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium national team]].

==Club career==
===Hamburger SV===
Onana joined [[2. Bundesliga]] club [[Hamburger SV]] in mid-2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=HSV verpflichtet Amadou Onana|trans-title=HSV signs Amadou Onana|url=https://www.hsv.de/news/hsv-verpflichtet-amadou-onana|website=hsv.de|publisher=[[Hamburger SV]]|date=31 January 2020|language=German|accessdate=1 July 2020}}</ref> He made his professional debut for the club in the first round of the [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal]] on 14 September 2020, coming on as a substitute in the 60th minute against [[3. Liga]] side [[Dynamo Dresden]]. He scored a header in the 89th minute of the match, which finished as a 4–1 away loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/match-report/ma9100553/lineup/ |title=Germany {{!}} DFB-Pokal 2020/2021 {{!}} 1. Round {{!}} Dynamo Dresden 4–1 Hamburger SV|website=WorldFootball|date=14 September 2020 |access-date=14 September 2020}}</ref>

===Lille===
[[File:RC Lens - Lille OSC (17-09-2021) 9 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Onana playing for [[Lille OSC|Lille]] in 2021.]]

In August 2021, Onana joined French champions [[Lille OSC|Lille]] on a five-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Capitaine Des Espoirs Belges Amadou Onana Est Lillois !|trans-title=The Belgium U21's captain Amadou Onana is Lillois!|url=https://www.losc.fr/node/107071|publisher=[[Lille OSC|Lille]]|date=5 August 2021|language=fr|access-date=5 August 2021|archive-date=5 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210805111455/https://www.losc.fr/node/107071|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made 32 appearances in [[2021–22 Ligue 1]], scoring once,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Player |url=https://www.ligue1.com/player |access-date=9 August 2022 |website=Ligue1}}</ref> as well as appearing in all eight of the team's [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3480215/2022/08/05/everton-amadou-onana-transfer-lille/|title=Everton close to confirming Amadou Onana signing from Lille|date=5 August 2022|access-date=18 September 2024|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

===Everton===
Onana signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on a five-year contract on 9 August 2022 for a reported £33m including add-ons.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 August 2022 |title=Onana Joins Everton |url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2727797/onana-joins-everton |access-date=9 August 2022 |publisher=[[Everton F.C.]]}}</ref> He scored his first Premier League goal for Everton, a header from a corner, in a 2–1 home defeat against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 14 January 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |first = Gary| last= Rose|date=14 January 2023 |title= Everton 1–2 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64195234 |access-date=14 January 2023|website=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>

On 19 December 2023, Onana missed what would have been the winning penalty for Everton in their [[2023–24 EFL Cup]] quarter-final against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]. With the penalties standing at 4–3 in Everton's favour, Onana attempted a penalty with no run up. Onana proceeded to pass the ball along the ground past Fulham goalkeeper [[Bernd Leno]] who easily saved the attempt. Fulham would go on to win 7–6 in the penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67688634|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|title=Everton 1–1 Fulham (7–6 to Fulham on pens): Tosin Adarabioyo scores winning penalty|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=18 December 2023 }}</ref>

=== Aston Villa ===
[[File:St. Louis City vs Aston Villa (Jul 2025) 08 (Célio Pompeu, Amadou Onana).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Onana playing for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2025.]]

On 22 July 2024, Onana signed for fellow Premier League club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 July 2024 |title=Aston Villa announce Amadou Onana signing |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2024/july/22/villa-announce-onana-signing/ |access-date=7 July 2024 |publisher=Aston Villa F.C.}}</ref> signing a five-year contract in a transfer reported to be worth £50&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Townley |first=John |date=22 July 2024|title=Aston Villa complete £50m transfer as Unai Emery makes big statement |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/breaking-aston-villa-complete-50m-29537908 |access-date=22 July 2024|website=Birmingham Live}}</ref> On 17 August 2024, he scored on his Aston Villa debut in a 2–1 opening day victory against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{Cite web|first=Marissa|last=Thomas|title=West Ham United 2–1 Aston Villa|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c0jpg84009vt|date=17 August 2024|access-date=11 April 2025|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Two weeks later, Onana scored the opening goal of Villa's 2–1 victory against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. On 17 September, Onana scored Aston Villa's third goal in their 3–0 victory against [[BSC Young Boys]] on his UEFA Champions League debut for the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/champions-league/2024-2025/bsc-young-boys-v-aston-villa-uefa-champions-league-live_sto10341369/story.shtml|first=Ben|last=Southby|title=BSC Young Boys v Aston Villa: UEFA Champions League Live|date=17 September 2024|access-date=18 September 2024|website=Eurosport}}</ref>

==International career==
On 18 May 2022, Onana was named in the Belgium senior squad for the four [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League]] matches in June 2022 against [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], [[Poland national football team|Poland]] (twice) and [[Wales national football team|Wales]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2022/05/18/32-rode-duivels-voor-4-duels-in-juni-onana-en-openda-zijn-nieuw~1652868054575/ |title=32 Rode Duivels voor 4 duels in juni: Onana en Openda zijn nieuw |trans-title=32 Red Devils for 4 duels in June: Onana and Openda are new|website=Sporza|date=18 May 2022 |access-date=18 May 2022|language=nl}}</ref> 20-year-old Onana made his full international debut against the Netherlands on 3 June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Pierre|last=Deprez|title=Diables Rouges : Amadou Onana est bien le futur (capitaine) de notre équipe nationale|url=https://www.rtbf.be/article/diables-rouges-amadou-onana-est-bien-le-futur-capitaine-de-notre-equipe-nationale-11176322|publisher=[[RTBF]]|date=31 March 2023|access-date=11 April 2025|language=fr}}</ref>

On 10 November 2022, Onana was named in the final 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/roberto-martinez-selects-26-devils-world-cup |title=Roberto Martinez selects 26 Devils for the World Cup |publisher=[[Royal Belgian Football Association]] |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022}}</ref> He made two appearances at the tournament, appearing as a substitute in the first group game against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] and starting against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in the second. He was suspended for Belgium's final match, as the team drew 0–0 with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and were eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3953749/2022/12/02/amadou-onana-everton-belgium-world-cup/|title=How much will Belgium need to rebuild Amadou Onana after Belgium's World Cup catastrophe?|date=2 December 2022|access-date=5 November 2023|website=[[The Athletic]]}}</ref>

On 28 May 2024, Onana was selected in the 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |date=28 May 2024 |title=25 Devils go to Euro 2024 |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/25-devils-go-euro-2024 |publisher=Royal Belgian Football Association |access-date=28 May 2024}}</ref> He played every minute of Belgium's four matches at the tournament, where they were knocked out by neighbours [[France national football team|France]] in the round of 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/teams/players/250117708--amadou-onana/statistics/|title=Amadou Onana: Statistics|access-date=18 September 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>

On 28 March 2026, Onana scored his first international goal in a 5–2 friendly victory over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Iglesias Maurer |first=Pablo |date=28 March 2026 |title=Rampant Belgium deliver 5-2 embarrassment to USA in World Cup tune-up |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/mar/28/belgium-usmnt-friendly-match-report |access-date=30 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==Personal life==
{{Unreliable sources|section|date=April 2025}}
Onana was born in [[Dakar]], Senegal, to a Senegalese mother and a Cameroonian father.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportmagazine.levif.be/foot-national/amadou-onana-espere-briller-en-ligue-des-champions-je-nai-pas-trouve-un-projet-qui-me-convenait-mieux-que-celui-du-losc/|url-access=subscription|first=Martin|last=Grimberghs|title=Amadou Onana espère briller en Ligue des Champions: " Je n'ai pas trouvé un projet qui me convenait mieux que celui du LOSC "|date=12 November 2021|access-date=6 July 2022|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtbf.be/article/amadou-onana-le-capitaine-des-diablotins-est-peut-etre-le-chainon-manquant-en-milieu-de-terrain-10996647|title=Amadou Onana : le Capitaine des Diablotins est peut-être le chaînon manquant en milieu de terrain}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/1053229/article/2021-08-05/football-mercato-qui-est-amadou-onana-la-nouvelle-recrue-du-losc|title=Football (mercato) : qui est Amadou Onana, la nouvelle recrue du LOSC ?|date=5 August 2021 }}</ref> At the age of 11, Onana, with his mother and sister, moved to [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] to join his father.<ref name=long>{{cite web|url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2785358/long-read-onanas-perseverance-and-pride|title=Long Read: Onana's Perseverance and Pride|date=8 September 2022|access-date=5 November 2023|publisher=Everton F.C.}}</ref>

Onana is a [[Muslims|Muslim]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64966647|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|title=Abdoulaye Doucoure: Everton midfielder on Islam, Ramadan, Idrissa Gueye and Amadou Onana|date=21 March 2023|access-date=5 November 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He is fluent in five languages: [[Wolof language|Wolof]], French, [[Dutch language|Dutch]], German and English.<ref>{{cite web |title='Andre's not even my name mate' 😅 {{!}} Amadou Onana jokes about how he became a meme |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=134&v=1DsyKZE3y9U&feature=youtu.be |via=YouTube | date=22 August 2024 |publisher=Sky Sports Premier League |access-date=28 October 2024}}</ref><ref name=long/> Outside of football, he also makes rap music under the name 24&nbsp;am, having released his debut single "Check On Me" on 2 August 2024.<ref>{{cite Instagram |user=its_onana |postid=C-LIqyfo9vw |date=2 August 2024 |title=My first ever track, who would've thought huh ? Be whoever you wanna be, that's all that matters. 'Check on me' by 24AM out on all platforms |access-date=2 September 2024}}</ref>

